\fs23\fsmilli11955 1.3 The Recognition Wager: Axioms First, Data Last, No Mercy\

\fs21\fsmilli10909 The core gamble of this work is brutally simple:\
Write down the smallest possible set of axioms that capture the act of physical recog-\
nition, and refuse to insert even a single empirical number thereafter. If the axioms\
are right, every constant in nature will be a logical consequence. If any constant resists\
derivation, the axioms are wrong\'97discard them and start over.\
4Non\'96negotiable rules of the wager.\
1. No mid\'96stream fitting. Once the eight axioms are stated, every subsequent chapter op-\
erates algebraically. Experimental data appear only at the end of a derivation as a pass/fail\
test, never as an input.\
2. Finite constructions only. Each proof reduces to counting, summing, or diagonalising\
finite objects. No appeal to unproven analytic conjectures or infinite renormalisations is\
allowed; all limits converge absolutely.\
3. Binary outcome. A single mismatch\'97one particle mass off by more than the quoted toler-\
ance, one cosmological parameter outside the derived band\'97invalidates the entire framework.\
Partial credit is impossible because there are no adjustable dials to retune.\
Why play such a harsh game? History shows that soft bets\'97those with tunable parame-\
ters\'97never close. Someone always finds a new measurement that forces the knobs to be readjusted,\
eroding predictive power. By contrast, an all-or-nothing wager delivers clarity regardless of the\
outcome:\
\'95 Win. The axioms survive every empirical test, demonstrating that physical law is an un-\
avoidable consequence of a minimal recognition principle.\
\'95 Lose. The first failed prediction pinpoints the exact logical fault line, revealing where new\
principles must enter. No ambiguity remains about \'93maybe the parameters were just off.\'94\
The remainder of the paper takes this wager at face value. It introduces the eight Recognition\
Axioms, derives their consequences step by step, and only then stacks those theorems against the\
full table of observed constants. No mercy\'97either the ledger balances to the last decimal or the\
theory is bankrupt.\
